The MongoDB MCP server is a tool that allows AI-powered development environments to interact directly with MongoDB databases and Atlas clusters using the Model Context Protocol [1][2]. It enables agents to perform data operations—such as querying, aggregation, and index management—as well as administrative tasks like managing Atlas cluster resources [2][3].

To use it, you must provide either a MongoDB connection string or Atlas API service account credentials (client ID and secret) [1][3]. The server can run locally via Node.js or in a Docker container [1][4].

Configuration example for your MCP client:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "MongoDB": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "mongodb-mcp-server@latest"],
      "env": {
        "MDB_MCP_API_CLIENT_ID": "your-client-id",
        "MDB_MCP_API_CLIENT_SECRET": "your-client-secret"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Atlas-specific administrative tools are only available when authenticating with Atlas API credentials [1][3]. You can restrict access by using the --readOnly flag in your configuration to disable write operations [4][3].
